covered: Valid Request: Multiple successful retrieval scenarios validate defaults, explicit parameters, and combinations (offset, limit, audit).
Empty Response: Covered via no bundles and offset beyond total returning empty arrays.
Pagination: Thoroughly exercised with small, medium, and large datasets; boundary conditions (negative, very large, beyond total) included.
Query Parameters: Valid enums (NONE default, FULL, MINIMAL) and invalid values; extra/ignored params; integer boundaries; max limit validation.
Server/Dependency Errors: Database unavailable (503) and timeout (504) covered.
Performance: Normal and peak-load response time expectations validated.
gaps: Rate Limiting: No scenarios validating throttling or 429 Too Many Requests behavior under bursty traffic.
Caching Behavior: No checks for ETag/Last-Modified or Cache-Control headers, nor conditional GET (If-None-Match/If-Modified-Since) handling.
Response Headers: Content-Type application/json not explicitly asserted; no validation of pagination-related headers if any are expected.
Authorization Variants: 403 (forbidden) not differentiated if applicable policy exists.
Result Consistency/Ordering: Deterministic ordering across pages not explicitly defined/verified beyond a single offset case (e.g., order by creation date or id).
recommendations: Add rate limiting tests: send rapid bursts and validate 429 or defined behavior and Retry-After header if applicable.
Add caching tests: verify ETag/Last-Modified and Cache-Control on 200 responses; perform conditional GETs expecting 304 Not Modified when appropriate.
Assert headers on success: Content-Type=application/json; include any pagination metadata headers if the API provides them.
Extend authorization tests to cover 403 (if role-based access applies) to distinguish authn vs authz failures.
Define and verify a stable sort order for pagination (e.g., by bundleId or createdDate) and ensure page boundaries are consistent across requests.
